motivation: currently the MessageConsumer end handler is called only when consumer is unregistered during an event bus close. When the consumer is explicitly unregistered it is not called. This handler is mainly used by RxJava and Kotlin coroutines and it seems it would be best to call the end handler in all case to give an opportunity to end the treatment. In RxJava it would call the complete handler and in Kotlin it would close the underlying channel (so a for-each iteration on the channel would terminate and execute the code after).

Change HTTP/1 outbound back-pressure to use eventual consistency to avoid race on missed signals: currently the HTTP/1 client request and server response use the TCP socket writability directly. As now a connection might use message passing with its streams, this can result in a missed back-pressure signal or an inacurate back-pressure measurement, e.b  writeQueueFull() might return a wrong value or a drain handler might not be called. Now each stream maintain its writability flag and will update it when the connection writability changes so the stream will always show the most recent value on this stream resulting in a loss of signal misses.

HTTP/2 ByteBuf handling should always copy the wrapped ByteBuf into a new ByteBuf instead of trying to reuse the ByteBuf when it is possible. Added test cases that will produce Buffer with a ByteBuf slices having a bound maxCapacity.

Buffer implementation now holds directly the reference to the ByteBuf instead of holding an unreleasable wrapper. When getByteBuf() is called, the returned ByteBuf is a buffer duplicate wrapped with an unreleasable wrapper, which achieve the same result. As consequence internal operations now operates directly on the ByteBuf and Buffer instances do not require to instantiate an unreleasable wrapper anymore. The implementation also now optimistacally assumes that Buffer arguments are the same implementation and will use the underlying ByteBuf directly avoiding to unnecessary duplicates that were done previously when calling getByteBuf() to get the ByteBuf. - close #3556

The ContextTest#testInternalExecuteBlockingWithQueue is subject to races. In order to be correct and assume that the thread will always be the same, the first task should wait until all blocking tasks are queued. Therefore we should wait until all blocking tasks are submitted during the first task execution to continue the execution.

Rename HttpServerRequest#upgrade to HttpServerRequest#toWebSocket and make it asynchronous in order to buffer the HTTP request body that is necessary to perform the WebSocket upgrade. Previously this buffering was done in the internal Http1xServerRequestHandler with a downside: upgrade requests are buffered and when delivered to a request handler instead of a WebSocket handler, then this handler will not get any HTTP events as those are already consumed to buffer the request body. Now the request handler will receive upgrade requests when the HTTP headers are received and can either set its own handler to handle the data or call toWebSocket to upgrade the connection to a WebSocket. - close #3564

Rename HttpServerRequest#netSocket to HttpServerRequest#toNetSocket, make it asynchronous and amend its behavior for HTTP/1.x . This method shall be used to create a tunnel from a CONNECT request. For HTTP/1.x it was also possible to use it for arbitrary requests to get a binary socket with the client, in practice this turns out to work only for event-loop applications because it modifies the channel pipeline (which precludes any usage for a worker application). Now HTTP/1.x behavior follows HTTP/2 behavior and the method is made asynchronous in order to perform pipeline modifications on the event-loop. - close #3562

Http1xClientConnection caches the expiration timestamp that is computed when the connection is recycled. When the connection is created by the pool but not used and immediately put back in the pool (it can happen with a slow TCP handshake) then the connection expiration timestamp field is not initialized and will tell the pool it is valid whatsoever. The connection remains usable like any other pooled connection however the pool policy will not apply to it (such as pool keep-alive setting).

The Http1xClientConnection is resumed and paused by the connection and individual streams. When those streams are dispatched on a different context than the connection context, there can be races due to miss notifications and the channel auto-read status remains paused preventing other HTTP streams to be received.

JsonObject/JsonArray provide a copy method that can fail on unknown elements when they cannot be copied by throwing an IllegalStateException. We can provide an overloaded version that uses a Function<Object, ?> to copy unknown elements and avoid failing.
Enable again commented HTTP/2 metrics parameterized tests

The HTTP/2 connection metric is registered agains the TCP metrics when the HTTP/2 connection preface is received. When an HTTP/2 connection is closed before the connection preface is received, the TCP metrics is signaled the connection unregistration without a prior connection registration. As side effect his can lead to incorrect state in a metrics implementation, such as a negative connection count.

CloseHooks and CloseFuture play a similar role, CloseHooks maintains a weak map of Closeable which can be CloseFuture. They can be unified in a unique class.

Context should always have a close future whether it is the deployment close future or the vertx close future and should not try to fallback on the vertx close future when none is provided. Likewise it should return the the close future.

Fix a regression in CloseFuture: a finalized closeable resource might be removed from the hooks after the list is copied and the close future will not progress. The close hooks should be copied before.

The reply handler result promise can be completed more than one time resulting in internal failures, this promise should be completed only once. The reply handler delivery performs a lookup on the reply handler and then schedule the message delivery on its event loop. There is a race happening when the reply timeout fires after the lookup and before the message delivery.
